door stood wide open, but nobody seemed at
hand.

As I hesitated whether to go off at once, or
return and seek my mistress, a slight cough
drew my attention to the hearth.

Linton lay on the settle, sole tenant, sucking
a stick of sugar-candy, and pursuing my move-
ments with apathetic eyes.

"Where is Miss Catherine?" I demanded,
sternly, supposing I could frighten him into
giving intelligence, by catching him thus,
alone.

He sucked on like an innocent.

"Is she gone?" I said.

"No," he replied; "she's up stairs--she's
not to go; we wont let her."

"You wont let her, little idiot!" I ex-
claimed. "Direct me to her room immediately,
or I'll make you sing out sharply."

"Papa would make you sing out, if you at-
tempted to get there," he answered. "He
